\begin_layout Subsection
Convergence and stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have run 1,000,000 simulations using pseudo-random numbers (rnorm native
 function in R) and low-discrepancy numbers (Sobol, Niederreiter and Halton).
 With this data, i obtain a convergence diagram that compares the convergence
 of these 3 types of numbers.
 The simulation that uses pseudo-random number is the slowest to converge:
 we can still observe significant variation in spread after 300,000 simulations.
 On the other hand, simulations that use Sobol and Niederreiter numbers
 seem to stabilize after 100,000 simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pseudo-random number generators can be used as number pipelines.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
These generators have no built-in mechanism for sampling efficiency (each
 draw has no knowledge of the previous draw).
 They typically lead to clusters and gaps which may or may not be desirable.
 They emulate randomness.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Low-discrepancy number generators 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
These algorithms are designed to take advantage of our knowledge of the
 dimensionality and ordering of importance of the given simulation problem
 at hand.
 It is an holistic scheme aiming for as little randomness as possible.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Monte carlo simulation using low-discrepancy numbers are, in theory, expected
 to converge as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\thicksim c(d)\frac{(\log N)^{d}}{N}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
whereas the convergence using pseudo-random numbers is, expected to be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\thicksim\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}
\]

\end_inset


