\begin_layout Section
Interest Rate Derivatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Heath–Jarrow–Morton (HJM) framework is a framework that model the evolution
 of the yield curve by representing the evolution of the instantaneous forward
 rates.
 This model impose the no-arbitrage restriction: the drift can't be random
 and depends on the volatility of forward rates.
 In HJM, volatility of forward rates is estimated from historical interest
 rate data (historical forward rates in our case).
 We will show how the principal component analysis is conducted (estimation
 and analysis of covariance matrices) to identify the major factors which
 influance the evolution of the yield curve before describing the projection
 of the forward curve and the pricing of various interest rate derivatives
 instrument using Monte Carlo simulation (using pseudo-random and low-discrepanc
y numbers).
 We use an OIS
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Overnight indexed swap
\end_layout

\end_inset

 spot curve as discounting curve in order to reflect the cost of funding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model, hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Forward rate notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Forward rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $F(t;T,S)$
\end_inset

 is the complete notation for the forward rate available at time t for the
 period starting a time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 (re-set or expiry time of the forward) and ending at time 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (maturity or the loan/deposit or cashflow payment time)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Instantaneousforward rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The instantaneous forward rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t,T)$
\end_inset

, as seen from some time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, start at time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and applies over an instant 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(t;T,S)\rightarrow f(t,T)\mbox{ when }S\rightarrow T^{+}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
It is a number from a continusous process:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f(t,T) & = & -\lim_{\varDelta t\rightarrow0}\frac{\log Z(t;T+\varDelta t)-\log Z(t;T)}{\varDelta t}\\
 & = & -\frac{\partial}{\partial T}\;\log\; Z(t;T)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Forward rates are bootstrapped using actual or synthetic zero-coupon bonds
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(t;T)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Heath–Jarrow–Morton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Single-factor HJM model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The stochastic differential equation for an instantaneous forward rate is
 written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
df(t,T)=m(t,T)dt+\nu(t,T)dX
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m(t,T)$
\end_inset

 is the risk-neutral drift represented by no arbitrage condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m(t,T)=\nu(t,T)\intop_{t}^{T}\nu(t,s)\; ds
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The risk-neutral drift depends on volatility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
A single-factor model for a spot interest rate cannot hope to capture the
 richness of the yield curves observed in practice.
 Generally speaking, a spot rate model with one source of randomness may
 be good at reflecting the overall level of a yield curve but fails when
 it comes to shifts in the yield curve that are substantially different
 at different maturities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Multi-factor HJM model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
The 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional stochastic differential equation (multi-factor HJM) is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
df(t,T)=m(t,T)dt+\sum_{i=1}^{N}\nu_{i}(t,T)dX_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m(t,T)$
\end_inset

 is the risk-neutral drift represented by no arbitrage condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m(t,T)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\nu_{i}(t,T)\intop_{t}^{T}\nu_{i}(t,s)\; ds
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Multi-factor means adding sources of randomness 
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Foactos must be uncorrelated, otherwise their impact would be overlapping
 and the model would require cross-terms and estimation of correlations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[dX_{i}dX_{j}\right]=\rho dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Musiela parametrization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to model the volatity of the forward rate for various maturities
 (6 months, one year, two years, etc.) and not at each maturity dates (1
 Jan 2014, 1 Jun 2014, etc.).
 Therefore we need to re-parameterise the volatility, the drift and the
 stochastic differential equation as function of tenor time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=T-t$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 the volatility function expressed as a function of tenor time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu(t,T)=\overline{\nu}(t,T-t)=\overline{\nu}(t,\tau)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Single-factor HJM model (Musiela parametrization)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The stochastic differential equation for an instantaneous forward rate (expresse
d as a function of tenor time) is written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\overline{f}(t,\tau)=\overline{m}(t,\tau)dt+\overline{\nu}(t,\tau)dX
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{m}(t,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the risk-neutral drift (expressed as a function of tenor time):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{m}(t,\tau)=\overline{\nu}(t,\tau)\intop_{0}^{\tau}\overline{\nu}(t,s)\; ds+\frac{\partial}{\partial\tau}\overline{f}(t,\tau)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multi-factor Musiela parametrization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Multi-factor HJM model (Musiela parametrization)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional stochastic differential equation is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\overline{f}(t,\tau)=\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,\tau)\intop_{t}^{T}\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,s)\; ds+\frac{\partial\overline{f}(t,\tau)}{\partial\tau}\right)dt+\sum_{i=1}^{k}\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,\tau)dX_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The model work with 
\begin_inset Formula $k<N$
\end_inset

 volatility functions that determine the diffusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 independant factors represented by the uncorrelated Brownian Motions 
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Pricincipal component analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Covariance matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariance matrix is obtained by following these steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Gather a 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix of historical forward rates (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the number of maturities).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate an 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix of daily differences (log differences since we are using data in
 a low-rate regime - from June 2011 to May 2014)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the covariance of the matrix of daily changes expressed in percentages
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma_{daily}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(m\times m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Obtain the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma$
\end_inset

 of (annualised and expressed in decimal) as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varSigma=\frac{252}{100\times100}\varSigma_{daily}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Principal component analysis idea
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to understand the factors that drive the evolution of the forward
 curve.
 We can identify these factors by decomposing the covariance matrix of differenc
es (i.e compute the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the covariance matrix).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varSigma=V\Lambda V^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the matrix with eigenvalues along its diagonal and zeros elsewhere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda=\begin{pmatrix}\lambda_{1}\\
 & \ddots\\
 &  & \lambda_{n}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a matrix with eigenvectors in its column
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\left(e^{(1)},\ldots,e^{(n)}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 is associated to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

, the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 is associated to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

, etc.
 The eigenvectors are orthogonal projections of the changes in data in direction
s of minimum variance.
 There are several ways to decompose matrices.
 We choose the Jacobi method which is not very computationaly efficient
 but has the advantage of keeping the structure of the original covariance
 matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We select 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues to serve as volatility
 functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,T)=\sqrt{\lambda_{i}}e^{(i)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The first entry in any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{(i)}$
\end_inset

 represents the movement of the one-month rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0.08$
\end_inset

), the second entry is the the two-month rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0.17$
\end_inset

) and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Jacobi transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jacobi transformation is a tractable numerical method to obtain eigenvalues
 and eigenvectors (diagonalisation).
 The main idea is to eliminate largest off-diagonal element by rotating
 the matrix at each iteration.
 The following steps describe the algorithm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the sum of the square of the elements of the upper triangle of
 the input matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continue to next step if this sum is more than the expected tolerance; otherwise
 stop recursive process and obtain the eigenvalues from the diagonal of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Identify the largest off-diagonal element 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{p,q}$
\end_inset

 of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the rotation matrix angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 required to eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{p,q}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tan(2\phi)=\frac{2\sigma_{p,q}}{\sigma_{q,q}-\sigma_{p,p}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the rotation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{p,q}$
\end_inset

 as 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{p,q}=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}1\\
 & \ddots &  &  &  & 0\\
 &  & \cos(\phi) & \cdots & \sin(\phi)\\
 &  & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
 &  & -\sin(\phi) & \cdots & \cos(\phi)\\
 & 0 &  &  &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  &  &  & 1
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma^{R}=(P_{p,q})^{T}\times\Sigma\times P_{p,q}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Loop back to step 1 and take 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma^{R}$
\end_inset

as input (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\Sigma^{R}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
This method is computationaly inefficient as each rotation destroys zeros
 obtained at previous step; however it achieves convergence.
 The covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma$
\end_inset

 becomes a diagonal matrix with eigen values in its diagonal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma\implies\Lambda=\begin{pmatrix}\lambda_{1}\\
 & \ddots\\
 &  & \lambda_{n}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eigenvectors are recovered by iteratively multiplying the rotation matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{p,q}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=P_{0}\times P_{1}\times\ldots\times P_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the number of iterations required to reach the expected tolerance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Volatility fitting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen, HJM drift calculation requires an integration.
 In order to perform an integration, we need to fit these volatility numbers
 to a function.
 Polynomial fitting by cubic spline is a popular choice.
 It means finding a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\beta_{0},\beta_{1},\beta_{2},\beta_{3})$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 so that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}(t,T)=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\tau+\beta_{2}\tau^{2}+\beta_{3}\tau^{3}$
\end_inset

approximates the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}_{i}(t,T)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
There are alternatives to to cubic spline fitting: multi splines or piecewise
 cubic spline (fit parts of the curve with different splines) or a logarithmic
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b\log\tau$
\end_inset

for the first component
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Zero-Coupon Bond pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Zero coupon bond price in HJM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
The ZCB price comes from the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $dZ=r(t)dt$
\end_inset

 under the risk- neutral measure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Z(t;T) & = & \mathbb{E^{Q}}\ensuremath{\left[\exp\left(-\int_{t}^{T}r(s)\; ds\right)\right]}\\
 & = & \mathbb{E^{Q}}\ensuremath{\left[\exp\left(-\int_{t}^{T}f(t,s)\; ds\right)\right]}\\
 & = & \mathbb{E^{Q}}\ensuremath{\left[\exp\left(-\int_{0}^{\tau}\overline{f}(t,s)\; ds\right)\right]}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
LIBOR pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Continuous compounded LIBOR rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
LIBOR is equal to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yield of a future-starting fairly priced ZCB.
 The LIBOR rate 
\begin_inset Formula $L(t;T)$
\end_inset

 that resets at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and is paid until maturity time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(t;T)=-\frac{\log Z(t;T)}{T-t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Continuous compounded LIBOR rate in HJM (Musiela parametrisation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Since we know 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(t;T)=\exp(-\int_{t}^{T}f(t,s)\; ds)$
\end_inset

, we can derive the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
L(t;T) & = & -\frac{\log Z(t;T)}{T-t}\\
 & = & -\frac{\log(\exp(-\int_{t}^{T}f(t,s)\; ds))}{T-t}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{T-t}\int_{t}^{T}f(t,s)\; ds\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\tau}\int_{0}^{\tau}\overline{f}(t,s)\; ds
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=T-t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Simple annualised LIBOR rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The simple annualised LIBOR rate (i.e the standard LIBOR rate) can be expressed
 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L^{'}=m(e^{\frac{L}{m}}-1)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the couponding frequency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
In our context, we work with 3M LIBOR.
 Therefore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{3M}=4(e^{\frac{L}{4}}-1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cap/Floor pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Caplet price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A caplet is an interest option that pays a cashflow based on the value of
 LIBOR at a reset time 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The cashflow is paid for the period from reset (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i})$
\end_inset

 to maturity (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i+1})$
\end_inset

 in arrears and therefore discounted to the current time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z(0;T_{i+1})\times\max\left[L(T_{i},T_{i+1})-K,0\right]\times\tau\times N=Z(0;T_{i+1})\times\left(L(T_{i},T_{i+1})-K\right)^{+}\times\tau\times N
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $L(T_{i},T_{i+1})$
\end_inset

 is the forward LIBOR rate (simple annualised) that resets at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 and matures at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i+1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=T_{i+1}-T_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the year fraction that converts the annualised rate to the period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the notional (we will scaled to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 going forward)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Cap price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Cap}(t;T;K)$
\end_inset

 starts at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (beginning of first period) and matures at 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 It can be decomposed into 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 caplets of shorter maturities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Cap}(t;T;K)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\mbox{Cpl}_{i}(T_{i},T_{i+1},K)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
If we assume 3M maturity caplets, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\frac{T-t}{4}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we can express the cap discounted payoff (price) as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Cap}(t;T;K)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}Z(0,T_{i+1})\times\left(L(T_{i},T_{i+1})-K\right)^{+}\times\tau\times N
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Buying a caop allows protection from increase in LIBOR rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L-(L-K)^{+}=\min(L,K)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Floor price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The price of a floor can be obtained from the price of a cap using this
 cap/floor relationship formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Cap}(t;T;K)-\mbox{Floor}(t;T;K)=N\sum_{i=1}^{n}L(T_{i},T_{i+1})\times\tau\times Z(0,T_{i+1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Floorlet price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The price of a floorlet can also obtained from the price of a caplet using
 this caplet/floorlet relationship formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Caplet}(T_{i};T_{i+1})-\mbox{Floorlet}(T_{i};T_{i+1})=L(T_{i},T_{i+1})\times\tau\times Z(0,T_{i+1})\times N
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Swaption pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Vanilla payer swaption price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We can write the discounted payoff of a payer swaption by considfering the
 value of the underlying payer IRS at its first reset dat 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (it is also maturity of the option embedded in the swaption):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\sum_{i=1}^{n}(L(T_{i},T_{i+1})-K)\times\tau\times Z(t,T_{i+1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The option will be exercised only if the above value is positive.
 In order to obtain the swaption payoff at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we need to apply the positive-part operator.
 Discounting this payoff at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to the current time, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{PayerSwaption}(t;T;K)=N\times Z(0,t)\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}(L(T_{i},T_{i+1})-K)\times\tau\times Z(t,T_{i+1})\right)^{+}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Black76
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market quotes Caps/Floors and Swaptions in terms of implied volatility.
 The below formula will help us to convert the prices we obtain via HJM
 as Black76 implied volatilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Caplet/Floorlet pricing with Black76
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The price of a caplet using Black76 can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Cpl}^{Bl}(0,T_{i},T_{i+1},K,\zeta_{i})=Z(0,T_{i+1})\times\tau_{i}\times\mbox{Black76}(K,F_{i}(0),\zeta_{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Black76}(K,F_{i}(0),\zeta_{i})$
\end_inset

 is the Black formula defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{Black76}(K,F_{i}(0),\zeta_{i}) & = & \mathbb{E^{Q}}\left[F_{i}(t)-K\right]^{+}\\
 & = & F_{i}(0)\Phi(d_{1})-K\Phi(d_{2})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d_{1} & = & \frac{\log\frac{F}{K}+\frac{\zeta^{2}}{2}}{\zeta}\\
d_{2} & = & \frac{\log\frac{F}{K}-\frac{\zeta^{2}}{2}}{\zeta}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in these formulae 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{2}=\zeta_{i}^{2}T_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The cap price is simply calculated as the sum of its captlet prices as we
 have seen in definition 27
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Cap/Floor implied volatility with Black76
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We find the implied volatility using a simple root finding procedure (Bisection
 or Newton-Raphson methods) applied on the cap price formula.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
We assume that volatility is constant thoughout the cap; i.e.
 all caplets are priced with the same volatility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Swaption pricing with Black76
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition

\color red
A REVOIR
\color inherit
.
 The price of a swaption using black76 can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{PayerSwaption}(t,T,\tau,K,\sigma_{\alpha,\beta})=\sum_{i=\alpha+1}^{\beta}\tau_{i}\times Z(t,T_{i+1})\times\left[S(t,\alpha,\beta)\Phi(d_{1})-K\Phi(d_{2})\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d_{1} & = & \frac{\log\left(\frac{S(t,\alpha,\beta)}{K}\right)+\frac{\sigma^{2}(T_{\alpha}-t)}{2}}{\sigma\sqrt{\left(T_{\alpha}-t\right)}}\\
d_{2} & = & \frac{\log\left(\frac{S(t,\alpha,\beta)}{K}\right)-\frac{\sigma^{2}(T_{\alpha}-t)}{2}}{\sigma\sqrt{\left(T_{\alpha}-t\right)}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

