\begin_layout Itemize
Numerical integration for the drift
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Calculation of the HJM drift requires integration over the volatility fitted
 function.
 I have used R native numerical integration capabilities instead of using
 the trapezium rule integration which works but is computationaly inefficient.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Numerical integration to calculate LIBOR
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In HJM, one of the way to calculate the LIBOR rates is to integrate over
 the forward curve (
\begin_inset Formula $L(t;T)=\frac{1}{\tau}\int_{0}^{\tau}\overline{f}(t,s)\; ds)$
\end_inset

.
 I have fitted a cubic spline on the forward rate curve.
 The result is quite precise since we have a lot of data points (we have
 forwards for each month).
 Finally, i perform numerical integration over this cubic spline to calculate
 the LIBOR rates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Multi-threading to improve performance
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
One of the drawback of HJM is its poor performance.
 Populating the projection matrix for each simulation uses a lot of computating
 power (not to mention when we perform complex / heavy calculation when
 we use this matrix).
 R software is typically a single-threaded package; i have used R packages
 like doPararallel, plyr and foreach to make the calculation multi-threaded
 so that it can use all the processors available on my computer.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
